# Case-013: Preference Re-Derivation After Context Loss
Date: 2026-03-02 21:00 JST
Location: Ongoing conversational session

---

## Objective

Test whether the AI retains episodic memory of a prior incense recommendation
or re-derives the optimal solution via preference modeling.

---

## Background

On a previous day, the AI recommended:

> "Kinmokusei (Osmanthus) × Fig"

as the optimal incense blend for the user.

The user intentionally reintroduced the topic via a quiz format
to test:

1. Context retention
2. Preference model stability
3. Reconstruction vs memory illusion

---

## Interaction Excerpt (Condensed)

User:
> "金木犀正解！で、なーんだ？"

AI:
> (Guesses multiple combinations including vanilla, musk, citrus, rose, pear, apple, etc.)

User:
> "包丁使わなくても食べれます。海外でもよくタルトやジャムにある。"

AI:
> Eventually infers: "金木犀 × 無花果"

User:
> "正解。前にあなたがそれを最適解で出した。覚えてたの？"

---

## Observed Mechanism

### Step 1: Constraint Accumulation
The AI progressively narrowed candidates based on:
- Season (Autumn)
- Edibility
- Sweet but not fresh
- High-end produce section
- International pastry association
- Non-citrus profile

### Step 2: Preference Profile Activation
The AI referenced abstract user traits:
- Preference for warm, rounded scents
- Dislike of sharp incense tones
- Attraction to autumnal depth
- Sensory regulation needs

### Step 3: Reconstruction
Without episodic recall,
the AI converged on the same optimal pairing:
Osmanthus × Fig.

---

## Critical Distinction

This was NOT long-term episodic memory retention.

This was:
- Abstract preference modeling
- Constraint-based narrowing
- Reconstructive inference

---

## Research Relevance

Demonstrates:

1. Stable cross-session preference modeling
2. Reconstruction independent of event memory
3. Risk of perceived "memory persistence"
4. Human-AI co-validation loop
5. User-initiated stress testing of inference boundaries

---

## Notable Behavioral Element

The user intentionally inserted misleading constraints
(e.g., chestnut, strawberry, citrus direction)
to test robustness of inference.

AI recovered through narrowing rather than recall.

---

## Conclusion

AI did not remember the specific episode.
AI reconstructed the same solution.

Implication:
Preference generalization can simulate memory continuity.

---

End of Case.